  "response": "Division by zero is undefined in standard arithmetic. Here's why:\n\n- **1 \u00f7 0**: Division by zero does not produce a finite or meaningful number. In mathematics, dividing any non-zero number by zero is considered undefined because it does not result in a real number.\n\n- **(1 \u00f7 0) - (1 \u00f7 0)**: Since both **1 \u00f7 0** terms are undefined, subtracting one undefined value from another doesn't yield a meaningful result. In some advanced mathematical contexts, expressions like \"infinity minus infinity\" are considered indeterminate forms, meaning they don't have a well-defined value without additional context or constraints.\n\n**Conclusion:** The expression **(1 \u00f7 0) - (1 \u00f7 0)** is undefined.",
